article.description: Lindsay Whalen had 22 points and eight assists and Connecticut outlasted Sacramento 82-78 in overtime Thursday night.
article.headline: Whalen's all-around play leads Sun's overtime charge
article.linkText: Sun rally, top Monarchs in OT for third straight win
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. -- The Connecticut Sun are back.

	   After struggling through a 1-8 stretch -- thanks in part to the
trade of Taj McWilliams-Franklin and an injury to key backup Erin
Phillips -- the Sun wrapped up a three-game road winning streak with
an 82-78 overtime victory over Sacramento Thursday night at Arco
Arena.

	   Lindsay Whalen made the key plays, including a layup with 2.8
seconds left in regulation to force the overtime, and finished with
22 points, eight assists and five rebounds.

	   Nykesha Sales topped all scorers with 23 for Connecticut (9-11),
which was playing without Asjha Jones, who wasn't with the team due
to a family emergency. Jones, who averages 15.9 points and 6.6
rebounds a game, may also miss Sunday's All-Star Game.

	   "Considering we played back-to-back, ... and considering we
without Asjha, and considering the hole we dug ourselves in the
first half [down 11], it was a great win," said Sun coach Mike
Thibault, referring to Wednesday night's win at Seattle,

	   And Connecticut, even after that dismal 1-8 stretch, would be in
the playoffs if the season ended today. "Everybody had to pick up
the slack," said Whalen about Jones' absence.

	   The Monarchs (12-8), on the other hand, need to regroup. Though
Nicole Powell and Adrian Williams each had 15 points, Sacramento
led by three, 66-63, with 1:13 left in regulation. But three missed
free throws in the last 16.1 seconds, and a defensive breakdown on
an inbounds play that allowed Whalen's wideopen, game-tying layup,
cost the Monarchs the game.

	   "The game was in our hands," said Sacramento coach Jenny
Boucek. "Some of it they did, but some of it was stuff we didn't
do."

	   It didn't help that All-Star Rebekkah Brunson was battling a leg
injury and couldn't get back into the game in the final minutes.
She finished the game with just five points and five rebounds in 21
minutes.

	   In the beginning, though, it looked like the Sun didn't need to
worry about Brunson, or overtime. Connecticut made its first five
shots and jumped out to a 10-2 lead, but the Monarchs responded
with a 13-0 run of their own.

	   Sacramento outscored the Sun 24-5 over the next 11:59, building
an 11-point lead -- but Connecticut then had a 19-4 edge in the
final 6:05, thanks in great part to Whalen, to go into the locker
room with a 34-30 lead.

	   Neither team could string much together in the second half, as
the lead changed hands a remarkable 17 times.
